ef>\n| [[73rd Golden Globe Awards|January 10, 2016]] \n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Best Animated Feature Film]]\n|-\n| [[Golden Reel Award (Motion Picture Sound Editors)|Golden Reel Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MOTION PICTURE SOUND EDITORS|url=https://mpse.secure-platform.com/a/gallery?roundId=6&searchParams=%7B%22pageIndex%22%3A0%2C%22sortMode%22%3A%22AscendingByApplicationName%22%2C%22displayMode%22%3A%22List%22%2C%22filterByApplicationCategoryPath%22%3A%5B59%2C67%5D%2C%22filterByWinnerCategoriesIds%22%3A%5B%5D%2C%22filterByFieldValues%22%3A%5B%5D%2C%22filterByApplicationNameOrCode%22%3A%22%22%7D|website=Motion Picture Sound Editors|accessdate=January 30, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304155742/https://mpse.secure-platform.com/a/gallery?roundId=6&searchParams=%7B%22pageIndex%22:0,%22sortMode%22:%22AscendingByApplicationName%22,%22displayMode%22:%22List%22,%22filterByApplicationCategoryPath%22:%5B59,67%5D,%22filterByWinnerCategoriesIds%22:%5B%5D,%22filterByFieldValues%22:%5B%5D,%22filterByApplicationNameOrCode%22:%22%22%7D|archivedate=March 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| February 27, 2016\n| Best Sound Editing: Sound Effects, Foley, Dialogue & ADR in an Animation Feature Film\n| Shannon Mills\n|-\n| [[Houston Film Critics Society Awards 2015|Houston Film Critics Society Awards]]\n| January 9, 2016\n| Best Animated Feature Film\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''The Good Dinosaur''\n|-\n| [[Online Film Critics Society|Online Film Critics Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Awards (19th Annual)|url=http://www.ofcs.org/awards/2015-awards-19th-annual/|website=Online Film Critics Society|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| December 14, 2015\n| [[Online Film Critics Society Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n|-\n| [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2015|Producers Guild of America Awards]]\n| January 23, 2016\n| Outstanding Producer of Animated Theatrical Motion Pictures\n| Denise Ream\n|-\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 San Diego Film Critics Society's Award Nominations|url=http://www.sdfcs.org/2015-san-diego-film-critics-society-award-nominations/|website=San Diego Film Critics Society|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2015 San Diego Film Critics Society Award Winners|url=http://www.sdfcs.org/2015-sdfcs-award-winners/|website=San Diego Film Critics Society|accessdate=December 15, 2015}}</ref>\n| December 14, 2015\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"| ''The Good Dinosaur''\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2015-satellite-award-nominees-announced-844739|title=Satellite Awards Nominees Unveiled|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Gregg |last=Kilday|date=December 1, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2015}}</ref>\n| [[20th Satellite Awards|February 21, 2016]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature|Best Motion Picture, Animated or Mixed Media]]\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]s<ref name=\"Saturn 42\">{{cite web|url=http://www.saturnawards.org/|title=The 42nd Annual Saturn Awards nominations are announced for 2016!|publisher=[[Saturn Award]]s|date=February 24, 2016|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n| [[42nd Saturn Awards|June 22, 2016]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Annual StLFCA Awards|url=http://www.stlfilmcritics.org/awards/|website=St. Louis Film Critics Association|accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n| December 20, 2015\n| [[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n|-\n| [[Village Voice Film Poll]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilday|first1=Gregg|title=The Dark Horse' Wins Top Honor at Seattle Film Fest|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/filmpoll/cat/animated_feature/2015|accessdate=January 15, 2016|work=Voice}}</ref>\n| January 7, 2016\n| Best Animated Film \n| {{draw|10th Place}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Visual Effects Society Awards 2015|Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"4\"| February 2, 2016\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in an Animated Feature\n| Sanjay Bakshi, Denise Ream, Michael Venturini, and Jon Reisch\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Animated Performance in an Animated Feature\n| Ana Gabriela Lacaze, Jacob Brooks, Lou Hamou-Lhadj, and Mark C. Harris (Spot)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Created Environment in an Animated Feature\n| David Munier, Matthew Webb, Matt Kuruc, and Tom Miller (The Farm)\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Simulations in an Animated Feature\n| Stephen Marshall, Magnus Wrenninge, Michael Hall, and Hemagiri Arumugam\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* [https://www.pixar.com/feature-films/the-good-dinosaur#the-good-dinosaur-1 Official website] at Pixar\n* {{IMDb title|1979388|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* {{tcmdb title|2007901|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* {{bcdb title|136933|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* {{Mojo title|pixar2013|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_good_dinosaur|The Good Dinosaur}}\n* {{Metacritic film|the-good-dinosaur|The Good Dinosaur}}\n\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar Animation Studios}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Cartoon|Animation|Film|United States|Dinosaurs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Good Dinosaur, The}}\n[[Category:2015 3D films]]\n[[Category:2015 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American alternate history films]]\n[[Category:American buddy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated buddy films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about death]]\n[[Category:Animated films about dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Animated films set in prehistory]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Children's comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:Dinosaur films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Sohn]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jeff Danna]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Mychael Danna]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric people in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:2015 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Good Dinosaur\n| image = The Good Dinosaur poster.jpg\n| alt = The silhouette of a dinosaur (apatosaurus) with a small boy on his back surrounded by stars\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Peter Sohn]]\n| producer = Denise Ream<ref name=LATYanks/>\n| screenplay = [[Meg LeFauve]]\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Sohn\n* Erik Benson\n* Meg LeFauve\n* Kelsey Mann\n* [[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/the-good-dinosaur-review-1201639759/|title=Film Review: \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Chang|first=Justin|date=November 13, 2015|accessdate=November 13, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Raymond Ochoa]]\n* Jack Bright\n* [[Sam Elliott]]\n* [[Anna Paquin]]\n* [[A. J. Buckley|A.J. Buckley]]\n* [[Steve Zahn]]\n* [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]]\n* [[Frances McDormand]]\n}}\n| cinematography = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sharon Calahan]] <small>(camera)</small>\n* Mahyar Abousaeedi <small>(lighting)</small>\n}}\n| music = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mychael Danna]]<ref name=VarietyPixarMold/>\n* [[Jeff Danna]]\n}}\n| editing = [[Stephen Schaffer]] \n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios<br/>Motion Pictures]]\n| released = {{Film date|2015|11|10|[[Paris]]|2015|11|25|United States}}\n| runtime = 94 minutes<!-- 93m 34s --><ref name=\"bbfc\">{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/good-dinosaur-2015|title=THE GOOD DINOSAUR &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $175 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/2015_film_study_v5_WEB.pdf|title=2015 Feature Film Study|last=FilmL.A.|date=June 15, 2016|page=25|access-date=June 17, 2018|via=}}</ref>\n| gross = $332.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pixar2013.htm |title=The Good Dinosaur (2015) |website=Box Office Mojo |access-date=August 20, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Good Dinosaur''''' is a 2015 American [[3D film|3D]] [[computer-animated]] [[drama (film and television)|drama film]]<ref name=ChristianPost>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/pixar-releases-trailer-for-the-good-dinosaur-video-141787/|title=Pixar Releases Trailer for 'The Good Dinosaur' (VIDEO)|work=Christian Post|access-date=August 2, 2015}}</ref> produced by [[Pixar|Pixar Animation Studios]] and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. Directed by [[Peter Sohn]] in his [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]] and written by [[Meg LeFauve]] from an original idea by [[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]], the film is set in an [[alternate history]] in which [[dinosaur]]s [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|never became extinct]]. The film follows a young and timid ''[[Apatosaurus]]'' named Arlo, who meets an unlikely human friend while traveling through a harsh, dangerous and mysterious landscape. The film features the voices of [[Raymond Ochoa]], Jack Bright, [[Sam Elliott]], [[Anna Paquin]], [[A. J. Buckley]], [[Steve Zahn]], [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]] and [[Frances McDormand]].\n\nPeterson, who came up with the idea for the story, directed the film until August 2013, to which in October 2014, Sohn was announced as the new director. The film, alongside ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'', marked the first time Pixar released two feature films in the same year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alexander|first1=Bryan|title='Inside Out' brings joy back to Pixar|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/06/18/pixar-inside-out-the-good-dinosaur/28879147/|work=USA Today|accessdate=June 19, 2015|date=June 18, 2015|quote=With ''Inside Out'' hitting theaters Friday and ''The Good Dinosaur'' expected Nov. 25, the company is releasing two films in the same year for the first time in its storied history.}}</ref>\n\n''The Good Dinosaur'' premiered on November 10, 2015 in Paris and was released in the United States on November 25, 2015. Despite positive reviews from critics and a total of $332.2 million worldwide against its $175 million budget, marketing costs lost Disney $85 million, causing ''The Good Dinosaur'' to become Pixar's first [[box-office bomb|financial disappointment]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |title='Good Dinosaur': Analyzing Pixar's First Box-Office Disaster |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/good-dinosaur-analyzing-pixars-first-857317 |accessdate=21 March 2019 |agency=The Hollywood Reporter |publisher=Billboard-Hollywood Reporter Media Group |date=22 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 and 700 words. -->\nIn an alternate history, [[Chicxulub impactor|the asteroid]] that would have caused the [[Cretaceous\u2013Paleogene extinction event|extinction of the dinosaurs 65 million years ago]] passes safely over Earth. Millions of years later, ''[[Apatosaurus]]'' corn farmers Henry and Ida have children: Libby, Buck and the runt, Arlo, who has trouble adjusting to farm life. While his successful siblings are allowed to \"make their mark\" (a mud-print on the family's corn silo), Arlo's timid nature makes tasks difficult for him. Henry attempts to give Arlo a sense of purpose by putting him in charge of guarding their silo, and helps him set a trap. It captures a caveboy, but Arlo cannot bring himself to kill him, and sets him free. Disappointed, Henry takes Arlo to track the caveboy, leading them into a ravine. Henry saves Arlo from a flash flood before being swept away and killed.\n\nWithout his father, Arlo shoulders more of the workload. He spots the same caveboy inside the silo and, blaming him for his father's death, chases him into a river, where he hits his head on a stone and is knocked unconscious. Awakening, he finds himself far from home and tries to survive on his own, but becomes trapped when a boulder pins his leg. The next day, Arlo wakes to find his leg has been freed, and the caveboy appears with food for him. The caveboy then leads Arlo to a berry tree, where the caveboy fends off a large snake, amazing Arlo and impressing a nearby eccentric ''[[Styracosaurus]]'' who wants to keep the boy. He forces Arlo to compete with him to give the boy a name he will respond to, which Arlo finally wins when he calls him \"Spot\". Arlo and Spot bond as Arlo laments his lost family, and Spot reveals that his own parents are dead. Later, when a storm strikes, Arlo runs away in fear and loses the riverbank he has been following home. The next morning, Arlo wakes to find Spot at his side. They are noticed by a band of [[pterodactyls]], led by Thunderclap, who appear to be conducting a rescue operation but turn out to be savagely carnivorous. When the pterodactyls try to take Spot, Arlo and Spot flee, happening upon a pair of ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' named Nash and Ramsey, who ward off the pterodactyls. Nash, Ramsey, and their father Butch have lost their herd of longhorns, so Arlo offers Spot's help in sniffing them out.\n\nThe group locates the herd, but Butch recognizes the work of cattle rustlers, and uses Arlo as a lure. Arlo and Spot attract the attention of four rustler ''[[Velociraptor]]'', allowing Butch and his family to attack. After the rustlers have been driven out of the pasture, Arlo joins the ''Tyrannosaurus'' in driving the cattle south when he sees the familiar mountain peaks of his homeland in the distance, and leaves with Spot to return home. Along the way, they encounter an adult feral caveman in the distance, and though Spot shows interest, Arlo dissuades him and they continue on. As another storm approaches, Thunderclap and the pterodactyls return and attack and carry Spot away. Arlo becomes entangled in vines, where he has a vision of Henry leading him home. Arlo instead resolves to save Spot, making the vision of his father proud before it fades away. Arlo finds and attacks the pterodactyls, who have cornered Spot at the river. Arlo and Spot together plunge Thunderclap and the pterodactyls into the water, where they are swept helplessly downstream. When another flash flood occurs, Arlo leaps into the water to rescue Spot as the two are swept away toward a waterfall. Arlo protects Spot as the two plummet down the fall, and carries him to shore. As they approach Arlo's home, the two again hear the unknown caveman call, and are approached by an entire cave family. With great reluctance, Arlo pushes Spot to join his adoptive family, and the two of them share a tearful goodbye. Arlo finally arrives home to his mother and siblings, and makes his mark on the silo between those of his mother and father.\n\n==Voice cast==\n<!--Do not add voice actors without official sources.--> \n<!--The species names must be consistent with the sources.-->\n* [[Raymond Ochoa]] as Arlo, a young ''[[Apatosaurus]]''<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2015/06/12/meet-the-new-cast-of-disneypixars-the-good-dinosaur/|title=Meet the New Cast of Disney\u2022Pixar\u2019s The Good Dinosaur |publisher=The Walt Disney Company|date= June 12, 2015|accessdate=June 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki>{{cite web|last1=Han|first1=Angie|title=\u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019 Preview: How John Ford and Hayao Miyazaki Helped Inspire Pixar|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/the-good-dinosaur-preview-how-john-ford-and-hayao-miyazaki-helped-inspire-pixar/|publisher=/Film|accessdate=June 18, 2015|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref>\n** Jack McGraw as Young Arlo\n* Jack Bright as Spot, a 7-year-old human [[Caveman|caveboy]] who befriends Arlo<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki/>\n* [[Sam Elliott]] as Butch, a ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' who runs a \"ranch\" filled with prehistoric \"longhorns\"<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/>\n* [[Anna Paquin]] as Ramsey, Butch's daughter<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki/>\n* [[A. J. Buckley]] as Nash, Butch's son<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki/>\n* [[Steve Zahn]] as Thunderclap, the leader of a gang of pterodactyls<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/>\n* Mandy Freund as Downpour, a pterodactyl who is a member of Thunderclap's flock<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n* Steven Clay Hunter as Coldfront, a pterodactyl who is a member of Thunderclap's flock<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n* [[Jeffrey Wright]] as Poppa Henry, the father of the ''Apatosaurus'' family, until his death<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki/>\n* [[Frances McDormand]] as Momma Ida, the mother of the ''Apatosaurus'' family<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/><ref name=SlashFordMiyazaki/>\n* [[Marcus Scribner]] as Buck, Arlo's older brother<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/>\n** Ryan Teeple as Young Buck<ref name=\"TGD-CharacterDesc\">{{cite web|title=\u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019 Official Character Descriptions|url=http://www.stitchkingdom.com/disney-good-dinosaur-character-descriptions-80841/|work=stitchkingdom.com|accessdate=November 10, 2015|date=November 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112213111/http://www.stitchkingdom.com/disney-good-dinosaur-character-descriptions-80841|archive-date=November 12, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n* Maleah Padilla as Libby, Arlo's older sister<ref name=\"TGD-CharacterDesc\"/>\n* [[Peter Sohn]] as Forrest Woodbush, a ''[[Styracosaurus]]'' who has various animals perched on his horns<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/><ref>{{cite web|last=Dougherty|first=Robert|title='The Good Dinosaur' Characters Receive Profiles|url=http://www.themovienetwork.com/article/good-dinosaur-characters-receive-profiles|publisher=themovienetwork.com|accessdate=October 12, 2015|date=October 12, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Boat]] as Bubbha, the leader of a gang of ''[[Velociraptor]]'' [[Cattle raiding|rustlers]]<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n* Carrie Paff as Lurleane, a ''Velociraptor'' who is a member of Bubbha's pack<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n* [[John Ratzenberger]] as Earl, a ''Velociraptor'' who is a member of Bubbha's pack<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n* Calum Mackenzie Grant as Pervis, a ''Velociraptor'' who is a member of Bubbha's pack<ref name=TGD-CharacterDesc/>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]] and [[Peter Sohn]] started working on the film in 2009, when Peterson came up with the idea.<ref name=MashableCreatedWorld>{{cite web|last1=Desta|first1=Yohana|title=How Pixar created the beautiful, dangerous world of 'The Good Dinosaur'|url=http://mashable.com/2015/09/17/the-good-dinosaur-tech-pixar/|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=September 18, 2015|date=September 17, 2015}}</ref> The film's first release date of November 27, 2013, was first announced in June 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bastoli|first=Mike|title=Untitled Pixar feature coming Nov. 27, 2013|url=http://www.bigscreenanimation.com/2011/06/untitled-pixar-feature-coming-nov-27.html|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Big Screen Animation|date=June 20, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317223610/http://www.bigscreenanimation.com/2011/06/untitled-pixar-feature-coming-nov-27.html#|archive-date=March 17, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The plot, director and co-director, producer and other small details were announced at the [[D23 Expo]] on August 20, 2011.<ref name=blog1>{{cite news|last=Rizvi|first=Samad|title=D23 2011: A Few More Details On Pixar\u2019s Dinosaur Movie|url=http://pixartimes.com/2011/08/21/d23-2011-a-few-more-details-on-pixars-dinosaur-movie/|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Pixar Times|date=August 21, 2011}}</ref> Peterson and [[John Walker (film producer)|John Walker]] announced the film as ''The Untitled Pixar Movie About Dinosaurs''.<ref name=\"blog1\"/> On April 24, 2012, Pixar announced that it would be titled ''The Good Dinosaur''.<ref name=PixarTimesTitle/>\n\nThe filmmakers wanted to explore what dinosaurs represent today, and how they are represented in stereotypes. Peterson stated: \"It's time to do a movie where you get to know the dinosaur, what it's really like to be a dinosaur and to be with a dinosaur.\"<ref name=24frames>{{cite news|last=Keegan|first=Rebecca|title=Pixar's 'The Good Dinosaur' will warm up a prehistoric reputation|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/movies/2012/05/pixars-the-good-dinosaur-.html|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=May 31, 2012}}</ref> Peterson said the inspiration for the project came from a childhood visit to the [[1964 New York World's Fair]] where he was impressed by some dinosaur [[Audio-Animatronics]].<ref name=\"24frames\"/>\n\nOn the film's title, Sohn stated, \"The title is deceptively simple. It has more meaning than it seems.\"<ref name=\"24frames\"/> He additionally explained: \"Arlo has a lot of issues when he's born. He's fearful and he's weak and he's disconnected from the family because of these issues and he feels like he's not worthy, and so he finds a way to become worthy.\"<ref name=YahooOverhaulCast/>\n\nIn April 2012, Pixar announced that the film's release date had been shifted from November 27, 2013 to May 30, 2014, with [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]]' ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' taking its place.<ref name=PixarTimesTitle>{{cite news|last=Rizvi|first=Samad|title=CinemaCon 2012: Pixar\u2019s Dinosaur Film Gets A Title, New Lee Unkrich Project Announced|url=http://pixartimes.com/2012/04/24/cinemacon-2012-pixars-dinosaur-film-gets-a-title-new-lee-unkrich-project-announced/|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Pixar Times|date=April 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rizvi|first=Samad|title=Pixar Dinosaur Film Bumped Off Nov 2013 Release Date|url=http://pixartimes.com/2011/12/23/pixar-dinosaur-film-bumped-off-nov-2013-release-date/|accessdate=March 1, 2013|newspaper=Pixar Times|date=December 23, 2011}}</ref> On August 9, 2013, it was announced at the D23 Expo that [[Lucas Neff]], [[John Lithgow]], [[Frances McDormand]], [[Neil Patrick Harris]], [[Judy Greer]], and [[Bill Hader]] had joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Beard |first=Lanford |url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/08/09/pixar-preview-the-good-dinosaur-spares-earth-an-asteroid-strike/ |title=Pixar preview: Casts announced for 'The Good Dinosaur,' 'Inside Out' |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=August 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Revisions===\nBy summer 2013, Peterson and Walker had been removed from the film due to story problems.<ref name=LATYanks/> Peterson, who could not crack the film's third act,<ref name=THRPixarVSDisney/> was absent from the D23 Expo where Sohn and producer Denise Ream presented footage from the film.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fischer|first=Russ|title=Rumor: \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019 Director Bob Peterson Is Off the Film|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/rumor-the-good-dinosaur-director-bob-peterson-is-off-the-film/|accessdate=August 30, 2013|newspaper=SlashFilm|date=August 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Drew|title=Pixar Filmmaker Bob Peterson Reportedly Off 'The Good Dinosaur,' Studio Seeking Replacement|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/pixar-filmmaker-bob-peterson-off-of-the-good-dinosaur-studio-desperately-seeking-replacement-20130826|accessdate=August 26, 2013|newspaper=The Playlist|date=August 26, 2013}}</ref> [[Pixar]]'s president [[Edwin Catmull|Ed Catmull]] explained the departure: \"All directors get really deep in their film. Sometimes you just need a different perspective to get the idea out. Sometimes directors... are so deeply embedded in their ideas it actually takes someone else to finish it up.\"<ref name=LATYanks/> Peterson moved on to another project he is developing at Pixar while Ream replaced Walker, who left to work on Disney's own ''[[Tomorrowland (film)|Tomorrowland]]''. On the subject of changing directors, Ream stated, \"Sadly, it happens more often than any of us would like... It's given a lot of thought and care. Bob still works at Pixar [and] he's a beloved member of the studio. He helps out on a lot of the movies. We care about him, but he just needed help getting the movie done.\"<ref name=io9Anders>{{cite web|last1=Anders|first1=Charlie Jane|title=How Pixar Rescued The Good Dinosaur From Creative Extinction|url=http://io9.com/how-pixar-rescued-the-good-dinosaur-from-creative-extin-1740125117|website=[[io9]]|accessdate=November 2, 2015|date=November 2, 2015}}</ref> [[John Lasseter]], [[Lee Unkrich]], [[Mark Andrews (filmmaker)|Mark Andrews]], and Sohn stepped in temporarily to work on various sections of the film.<ref name=LATYanks>{{cite news|last=Keegan|first=Rebecca|title=Pixar Animation yanks director Bob Peterson off 'The Good Dinosaur'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-pixar-director-20130831,0,3649321.story|accessdate=August 30, 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 30, 2013}}</ref> In September 2013, ''The Good Dinosaur'' was pushed back from May 30, 2014, to November 25, 2015 (the scheduled release date for Pixar's ''[[Finding Dory]]''). According to Ream, the primary reason for the rescheduling was \"the story was not working, period, full stop, it just was not where it needed to be.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|title=\u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019 Producer Denise Ream on Re-Casting the Voices and More|url=http://collider.com/good-dinosaur-producer-denise-ream-interview-pixar-movie/|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=November 7, 2015|date=November 5, 2015}}</ref> In November 2013, due to the delay, Pixar laid off 67 employees of its 1,200-person workforce,<ref name=THRPixarVSDisney>{{cite news|last=Kilday|first=Gregg|title=Pixar vs. Disney Animation: John Lasseter's Tricky Tug-of-War|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pixar-disney-animation-john-lasseters-661752|accessdate=December 4, 2013|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 4, 2013}}</ref> following the closure of [[Pixar Canada]] a month before, when about 80 employees had been laid off, officially to refocus Pixar's efforts at its main headquarters.<ref>{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Daniel|title=Pixar undergoes layoffs due to 'The Good Dinosaur' delay|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-pixar-layoffs-good-dinosaur-delay-20131122,0,6910438.story|accessdate=November 23, 2013|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=November 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the footage shown at the 2013 D23 Expo, Arlo was a huge dinosaur, Sohn recalled: \"In the original version of the film, Spot was so tiny, we really wanted to make him feel like a bug. But people had a tough time connecting that these two had a relationship, because Arlo was so large. It was fun, but at the same time we never believed the growth that they could have together. It was really like, 'I'm best friends with a bee!' Bob Peterson, the original director, his first pitch was just a boy and his dog, and so when I took it I said, 'I want to honor that as much as I can.'\"<ref name=\"DisneyInsider\">{{cite web|title=Director Peter Sohn on the Evolution of The Good Dinosaur|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2016/02/24/director-peter-sohn-on-the-evolution-of-the-good-dinosaur/|publisher=Disney Insider|accessdate=February 26, 2014|date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Lithgow revealed in an interview that the film had been dismantled and \"completely reimagined\" and that he was expected to rerecord his role in the next month, while mentioning that McDormand was still part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/the-good-dinosaur-story-details-john-lithgow/ |title=John Lithgow Says The Good Dinosaur Was Dismantled and Reimagined |publisher=Collider.com |date=May 30, 2014 |accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> In November 2014, it was reported that new elements had been added to the story, such as treating nature as the film's antagonist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Keegan|first=Rebecca|title=Pixar redraws the lines for 'Good Dinosaur'|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-pixar-good-dinosaur-peter-sohn-20141120-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=November 18, 2014|date=November 18, 2014}}</ref> Pixar's general manager and president [[Jim Morris (film producer)|Jim Morris]] stated, \"We all liked the movie from the beginning, but... the story had some kind of fatal flaws in it that none of us really saw. It was kind of a ''[[Billy Elliot]]'' story. It was a very different kind of movie\u2014there was a whole dinosaur culture and community and so forth. It was one where the Arlo character was kind of repressed by the community. It never quite felt right. It always felt like that we were vilifying this group [of dinosaur characters] that was otherwise a very likeable group. It just didn't feel like it resonated truly.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Edmund|title=Chinese film-goers may see Pixar's Good Dinosaur before US|url=http://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/article/1862093/chinese-film-goers-may-see-pixars-good-dinosaur-us|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=September 28, 2015|date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> Morris additionally explained: \"We give people the chance to work on a story, and we give them our support, but it doesn't always work out... there were story issues that were just not solvable. So we changed the story to make it better, and we're very proud of the film we have now.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Wai Yee|first=Yip|title=Pixar's first Asian-themed film to debut next month, along with The Good Dinosaur|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/pixars-first-asian-themed-film-to-debut-next-month-along-with-the-good|newspaper=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=October 2, 2015|date=October 1, 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, Sohn was announced as the new director of the film.<ref name=Newdirector>{{cite web|last1=Amidi|first1=Amid|title=Peter Sohn Named New Director of Pixar\u2019s \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/pixar/peter-sohn-named-new-director-of-pixars-the-good-dinosaur-104875.html|publisher=[[Cartoon Brew]]|accessdate=October 22, 2014|date=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that the majority of the cast had been revised.<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/> Of the original cast, only McDormand retained her role in the film. It was revealed that Neff had been replaced by [[Raymond Ochoa]], and Lithgow had been replaced by [[Jeffrey Wright (actor)|Jeffrey Wright]].<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/> Arlo's three siblings, to be voiced by Harris, Hader, and Greer had been cut down to a single brother named Buck, voiced by [[Marcus Scribner]],<ref name=\"TGD-Recast\"/> and later, a sister named Libby, voiced by Maleah Padilla. On the cast revisions, Sohn explained: \"It was all about finding a younger Arlo, it was really about finding a boy [to play Arlo], so that we could push into that idea of him growing up and becoming a man, so the actor previous\u2014who is a great actor\u2014he was already a man, and so I needed to push that arc and find that compassionate kid, so that was the major kind of change. Then everything else, all the other characters that supported that story came in and out and changed and evolved and through that evolution, some of those performers changed out of it.\"<ref name=YahooOverhaulCast>{{cite web|last=Butler|first=Tom|title=Why Pixar's The Good Dinosaur Had To Overhaul Its Voice Cast (Exclusive)|url=https://uk.yahoo.com/movies/why-pixars-the-good-dinosaur-had-to-overhaul-its-121662926996.html|work=Yahoo Movies UK|accessdate=June 17, 2015|date=June 16, 2015}}</ref> It was also confirmed that the farmer aspect was still part of the film.<ref>{{cite web|last=Douglas|first=Edward|title=A Special Sneak Preview of Disney\u2022Pixar's The Good Dinosaur|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/features/451419-a-special-sneak-preview-of-disney%E2%80%A2pixars-the-good-dinosaur#/slide/1|work=Comingsoon.com|accessdate=June 17, 2015|date=June 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Design and setting===\nThe filmmakers wanted nature to be the antagonist for the main character Arlo. Ream noted \"Nature can overcome anything, including a massive dinosaur.\" In order to achieve the needed realism, the film's team traveled to the [[Northwestern United States|American Northwest]], spending time in [[Jackson, Wyoming|Jackson Hole, Wyoming]], [[Juntura, Oregon]], and southern [[Montana]]. Production designer [[Harley Jessup]] stated: \"The area has a fantastic variety of landscapes, ranging from the Jackson Valley and the [[Teton Range|Tetons]] to the amazing geysers and waterfalls in [[Yellowstone National Park|Yellowstone]], we studied the grasslands of Montana and the [[Red Desert (Wyoming)|Red Desert]], then incorporated all of it in Arlo's journey.\" To use the landscapes that they had experienced, the filmmakers used data from the [[United States Geological Survey|U.S. Geological Survey]], and satellite images from [[Google Earth]]. The geographical data provided a foundation that the team then built on. According to supervising technical director Sanjay Bakshi, this gave Sohn \"the freedom to shoot in any direction he wanted to make the world feel big and real.\" In addition, ''The Good Dinosaur'' features three-dimensional, volumetric clouds. In previous Pixar films, clouds have been \"painted\" onto the sets. Light and photography director Sharon Calahan explained: \"Storm clouds are almost like a villain in the film. Plus, it's very labor-intensive to paint clouds, and they're in almost every scene.\" Calahan also noted \"These particular clouds can be rendered and we can light them, which we've never been able to properly do before.\"<ref name=\"Zakrzewski\"/><ref name=\"Lesnick\"/>\n\nAccording to the filmmakers, the environments and landscapes in the film are not photo-realistic, they are just detailed in a way that advanced technology and style decisions allow. In terms of animating Arlo, animators Rob Thompson and Kevin O'Hara went to a zoo and shot video of elephants in motion. Thompson stated: \"One of the most intimidating things to animate is a quadruped, because there's so much to them and there's so much to manage. It's very easy to make it not work if you don't know what you're managing. Locomotion is all about efficiency, a lot of times you think, 'We're animating a big, heavy character. We should slam those feet. That'll make it feel heavy.' The truth is, that's not efficient. That wouldn't be great for the legs.\"<ref name=\"Zakrzewski\">{{cite web|last=Zakrzewski|first=Cat|title=Pixar Studios Doubles Effects In Upcoming Film \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/10/09/pixar-studios-doubles-effects-in-upcoming-film-the-good-dinosaur/|newspaper=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=October 9, 2015|date=October 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Lesnick\">{{cite web|last=Lesnick|first=Silas|title=The Good Dinosaur Story: Behind the Scenes at Pixar|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/features/620701-the-good-dinosaur-story#/slide/1|website=Comingsoon.net|accessdate=October 9, 2015|date=October 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Zacuto\"/> A system where Arlo's head goes up and his chest goes down when his hips goes up, was therefore created. To get an idea of the scale of Arlo, a complete full-size model was built out of card and foam core. In total ''The Good Dinosaur'' took up 300[[Byte|TB]] of server space, ten times as much space as ''[[Monsters University]]'' (2013).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/how-pixar-changed-all-the-rules-to-make-the-good-dinosa-1735364564|title=How Pixar Changed All The Rules To Make The Good Dinosaur A Stunning Masterpiece|first=Charlie Jane|last=Anders|website=io9}}</ref>\n\nArlo was designed so that the audience could identify with him and be able to see the \"boy\" inside the dinosaur. Sohn explained \"When Arlo gets lost in the wilderness, you need to worry that he's out of his element and in danger of getting killed, rather than just thinking 'You're an animal. Why don't you just turn around and eat some leaves?'\" He additionally stated \"If you put like a realistic dinosaur in the woods, eat some leaves, you're fine... But we really wanted to play with that twist of this is a boy out there. A dinosaur boy for sure, but trying to infuse those qualities into him... And also keeping him in a world that had an arc to itself. That it would start off being beautiful and then become dangerous. When we had these designs of the trees where they were a little bit more blocky and a little bit more graphic. We put Arlo in front of it, it's like 'ooh that kind of is cool, but boy, it doesn't feel like it's that dangerous.' Like when we get a rock stuck on him, it didn't feel like anything 'cause when we went on our research trips, boy that idea of like you can get, you could die by a small thing like having a rock on your foot. Or you could die by a huge thing like an avalanche, which we tried to kind of explore in the film. So that was one of our main intents.\"<ref name=io9Anders/><ref>{{cite web|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|title=Interview: Director Peter Sohn Talks \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/peter-sohn-good-dinosaur-interview/|website=[[slashfilm.com|/Film]]|accessdate=November 2, 2015|date=November 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of the film's setting, Sohn stated \"Pixar is all about the 'what if' question... 'What if the asteroid missed the earth?' Yeah, we went down the road of: they could be cooking in a dino diner; they could be in space; they could be in anything. But then there was a drawing of a dinosaur farming that kind of sparked people of the idea of 'he's working hard and this character needs to survive out there.' All of the American dinosaur bones are found in the northwest\u2014from Montana, to [[Oregon]], to [[Wyoming]], and [[the Dakotas]], so the combination of hardworking farm families and the west really brought us into that frontier world immediately... [S]o we started doing research. We started finding all of these people who were surviving out there on the land. They were either cultivating the cattle, or were ranchers in Oregon, or were farmers in the Midwest. It just kept teaching us how much we want to honor this world, and how hard it is to survive out there. It started dictating the world itself.\"<ref name=\"DisneyInsider\"/>\n\nSince ''The Good Dinosaur'' is set in a world in which dinosaurs never became extinct, they were instead able to evolve. Herbivores like Arlo and his family become farmers, and carnivores like the ''T. rex'' become ranchers. Because they are meant to be reminiscent of cowboys, when the ''T. rex'' run, their lower bodies mimic a galloping horse, while their upper bodies have the feel of a riding cowboy. To help inspire Butch's physical look and performance, the filmmakers looked at classic film cowboys such as characters portrayed by [[Clint Eastwood]] and [[Jack Palance]].<ref name=Zacuto>{{cite web|last1=Zacuto|first1=Ben|title=EXCLUSIVE: GOOD DINO HD Stills and Fun Facts|url=http://www.everythingpixar.com/blog/exclusive-good-dino-hd-stills-and-fun-facts|website=EverythingPixar.com|accessdate=November 18, 2015|date=November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Anchor|Music|Score|Soundtrack}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Good Dinosaur\n| type       = Film score\n| artist     = [[Mychael Danna|Mychael]] and [[Jeff Danna]]\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| released   = November 20, 2015\n| recorded   = 2015\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Warner Bros. Eastwood Scoring Stage in Burbank, CA\n| genre      = [[Soundtrack]], [[film score]]\n| length     = 1:33:28\n| label      = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer   = Chris Montan\n| chronology = [[Pixar]] film soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Inside Out (2015 film)#Soundtrack|Inside Out: Original Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Finding Dory#Soundtrack|Finding Dory]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Mychael Danna]]\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[The Captive (2014 film)|The Captive]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| title      = The Good Dinosaur\n| year       = 2015\n| next_title = [[Storks (film)|Storks]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n| artist     = [[Jeff Danna]]\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| prev_title = [[Kurt Cobain: Montage of Heck|Montage of Heck]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| title      = The Good Dinosaur\n| year       = 2015\n| next_title = [[Storks (film)|Storks]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n}}\n}}\n\nThe film's score was composed by [[Mychael Danna]] and his brother, [[Jeff Danna|Jeff]],<ref name=VarietyPixarMold/> replacing [[Thomas Newman]], who was originally attached to score the film when it was set to be directed by [[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2015/05/20/mychael-danna-scoring-pixars-the-good-dinosaur/|title=Mychael Danna Scoring Pixar\u2019s \u2018The Good Dinosaur\u2019 &#124; Film Music Reporter}}</ref> It marks the first Pixar film to be scored by two composers.<ref name=VarietyPixarMold>{{cite news|last1=Burlingame|first1=Jon|title=\u2018Good Dinosaur\u2019 Score Breaks Pixar Mold|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/features/good-dinosaur-score-breaks-pixar-mold-1201632690/|accessdate=November 12, 2015|work=Variety|date=November 3, 2015}}</ref> Danna was approached by Sohn and Ream due to his score for ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'', which won an Academy Award.<ref name=VarietyPixarMold/> Having a lot of work, he invited his brother as a co-writer.<ref name=VarietyPixarMold/> [[Walt Disney Records]] released the soundtrack on November 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Walt Disney Records Releases \"The Good Dinosaur\" Original Motion Picture Soundtrack Score Composed By Mychael And Jeff Danna|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/walt-disney-records-releases-the-good-dinosaur-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-score-composed-by-mychael-and-jeff-danna-300182744.html|accessdate=December 7, 2015|work=PR Newsire|date=November 20, 2015|location=Burbank, California|format=Press release}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = The Good Dinosaur (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| all_music = Mychael Danna and Jeff Danna\n| total_length = 1:03:23\n| title1 = Homestead\n| length1 = 2:11\n| title2 = Hello Arlo\n| length2 = 2:49\n| title3 = Chores\n| length3 = 0:55\n| title4 = Make Your Mark\n| length4 = 2:07\n| title5 = Fireflies\n| length5 = 2:16\n| title6 = Critter Problem\n| length6 = 1:04\n| title7 = You're Me and More\n| length7 = 3:05\n| title8 = Family Struggle\n| length8 = 1:23\n| title9 = Swept Away\n| length9 